en_222667_0	Colombo (News1st): The Employees Provident Fund (EPF), a boon for the working people of Sri Lanka has sustained major losses due to investments in various businesses in the recent past.
en_222667_1	The Presidential Commission of Inquiry into large-scale corruption at Sri Lankan Airlines brought to light shocking revelations on misdealings with the resources of the EPF.
en_222667_2	A senior official at the EPF testified before the Presidential Commission of Inquiry today (October 01).
en_222667_3	She revealed that the EPF had invested a sum of Rs.
en_222667_4	495 million in Cargills Bank which was established recently.
en_222667_5	It was also revealed that the EPF is yet to receive any dividends as a result of this investment.
en_222667_6	There have also been no returns from an injection of Rs.
en_222667_7	5 billion into Canwill Holdings.
en_222667_8	Four persons including the former President’s Chief of Staff Gamini Senarath and Piyadasa Kudabalage served as directors of Canwill Holdings, they are currently facing legal action over irregularities in the Hyatt hotel project.
en_222667_9	Investigations have revealed that the money illegally invested from the EPF into Canwill holdings had then been defrauded by funneling it into a different company.
en_222667_10	It was also revealed today that EPF funds had been invested into two more hotel projects, with the EPF yet to receive any dividends from these investments.
en_222667_11	The testimony by  EPF official revealed that a sum of Rs.
en_222667_12	500 million belonging to the EPF had been invested in Sri Lankan airlines in the year 2010, when Emirates withdrew from managing the airline.
en_222667_13	The EPF official noted that this investment was made in violation of procedure as existing regulations dictate that EPF funds can only be invested in listed companies on the Colombo Stock Exchange.
en_222667_14	While approval must be sought from the Central Bank Governor for any investment outside these regulations, it was revealed that such approval had not been granted.
en_222667_15	The Governor of the Central Bank at the time was Ajith Nivard Cabraal.
en_222667_16	As per the Central Bank, the notational value of the Rs.
en_222667_17	500 Million investment in Sri Lankan Airlines is now a mere Rs.
en_222667_18	100.
